ales":"Llandyfeisant, Carmarthenshire, Wales","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Mercia","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Alessandro, Arcangelo, Vito.","Italian (Sicily): feminine form <b>Meccio</b>, which is probably a nickname from Sicilian <i>mecciu</i> ‘curl’, ‘ringlet’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705176,"age":25,"year":"0980","julianDay":2078998,"title":"Vikings Invade England","description":"Viking raiders from Scandinavia invaded England in 980. Years later in 991, the English government paid them 10,000 in hopes for peace. The Viking raiders, however, continued to force more money from England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705177,"age":39,"year":"0994","julianDay":2084112,"title":"Danes Attack London","description":"Danes and Norwegians attacked London unsuccessfully in 994.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Saxon_London#10th_century_London","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Anglo-Saxon London","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705178,"age":47,"year":"1002","julianDay":2087033,"title":"St. Brice's Day Massacre","description":"King Aethelred ordered all Danish men in England to be killed. It is unknown how many Danes were killed due to this order.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Eadwyne ap Aelfwyne of Mercia was born about 0955, in England as the son of Ælfwine of Mercia. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs Eadwyne."},"et":{"about 0955–":"umbes 0955–Surnud"